"{\"uid\": \"rnz.co.nz-news-olympics-2024-524572-olympics-2024-sailors-erica-dawson-and-micah-wilkinson-claim-bronze-in-nacra-mixed-multihull\", \"text\": \"Erica Dawson and Micah Wilkinson in action in the medal race.Photo:AFP/CHRISTOPHE SIMON  New Zealand sailorsErica Dawson and Micah Wilkinsonhave claimed Olympic bronze in the Nacra mixed multihull in Marseille.  The duo finished eighth in the final, but took the medal on points.  Their closest competition for the bronze heading into the race was Great Britain, who were disqualified for a false start.  The Brits were unaware of their indiscretion, and raced on until the umpires pulled them out.  Italy took the gold while Argentina won silver.  The Kiwi sailors embrace after crossing the finish line.Photo:AFP/NICOLAS TUCAT  The French cruised to the finish, well out in front of the rest of the pack, but were out of medal contention and finished in fifth place overall.  There were some late concerns over wind strength and a potential abandonment as it dipped below five knots, but the race was completed without further drama.  The win took New Zealand's medal tally to 11.  Speaking to Sky Sport after the race, Dawson said the duo were in a state of disbelief and happiness.  \\\"I just can not believe it. It's so cool.\\\"  Wilkinson said the pair had raced together for five years and only medalled at one event.  \\\"To do it when it matters is an incredible feeling.\\\"  Copyright \\u00a92024,Radio New Zealand  NZ cyclist Ellesse Andrews has won the women's keirin final comfortably, while Lisa Carrington's crew have claimed a win in the K4.  New Zealand's first five sailors selected for the Paris 2024 Olympic Games represent Aotearoa's future on the water.  An Otago PE teacher has been on the edge of his seat as two of his former students have claimed Olympics medals - and the whole town has been celebrating, he says.Audio  Eight years on from her Olympic debut, Eliza McCartney re-entered the Games arena much the same way she left it - joyous, exuberant, awestruck.  for ad-free news and current affairs  Olympics 2024 RSS  Follow RNZ News\"}"